candidates.solution:
**Solution Outline**

For a set of points in the plane a point is *sparkling* iff it is **not strictly inside** the convex hull of the other points.  
Consequently a sparkling point is exactly a point that lies on the boundary of the convex hull (vertices and points that are collinear with an edge of the hull).

The required distance is therefore the *diameter* of the convex hull – the largest Euclidean distance between any two points that belong to the hull.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 1.  Geometry primitives

*Cross product*  
For two vectors `a = (ax, ay)` and `b = (bx, by)`  
`cross(a, b) = ax*by – ay*bx`.  
It is positive if `b` is to the left of `a`, negative if to the right, and zero if they are collinear.

*Squared distance*  
`dist2(p, q) = (p.x – q.x)² + (p.y – q.y)²`.  
We use the squared distance to avoid floating point arithmetic; the answer is the same because the square root is monotone.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 2.  Convex hull – monotone chain

1. Sort all points by `(x, y)`.  
2. Build the lower hull: iterate over sorted points, while the last two points of the hull together with the current point make a **right turn** (cross < 0) pop the last point.  
3. Build the upper hull in the same way, iterating from the end of the sorted list.  
4. Concatenate lower and upper hulls, removing the last point of each part to avoid duplication of the first point.

The algorithm runs in `O(n log n)` because of the sorting step.  
All points that lie on the boundary of the convex hull (including collinear ones) are kept, which is exactly what we need for sparkling points.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 3.  Rotating calipers – diameter of a convex polygon

Let the hull vertices be `h[0 … m-1]` in counter‑clockwise order.

```
ans = 0
j = 1
for i = 0 … m-1:
    next_i = (i + 1) mod m
    # Move j while the area of triangle (h[i], h[next_i], h[(j+1) mod m]) is larger
    while cross(h[next_i] - h[i], h[(j+1) mod m] - h[i]) >
          cross(h[next_i] - h[i], h[j] - h[i]):
        j = (j + 1) mod m
    ans = max(ans, dist2(h[i], h[j]))
    ans = max(ans, dist2(h[next_i], h[j]))
```

The loop visits each edge once and `j` only moves forward, so the total time is `O(m)`.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 4.  Correctness Proof  

We prove that the algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between two sparkling points.

---

#### Lemma 1  
A point is sparkling iff it belongs to the boundary of the convex hull of the whole set.

*Proof.*  
If a point lies strictly inside the convex hull of the other points, it is not sparkling by definition.  
Conversely, if a point lies on the boundary of the convex hull, it cannot be expressed as a convex combination of the other points, hence it is not strictly inside the hull of the others and is sparkling. ∎



#### Lemma 2  
The monotone chain algorithm returns all points that lie on the boundary of the convex hull (including collinear points on edges).

*Proof.*  
During construction of each hull part, a point is removed only when it would create a right turn, i.e. when it lies strictly inside the current hull.  
Collinear points are never removed because the cross product is zero, not negative.  
Thus every point that is on the boundary remains in the final hull. ∎



#### Lemma 3  
For a convex polygon, the rotating calipers procedure enumerates all antipodal pairs of vertices.

*Proof.*  
The standard rotating‑calipers argument shows that for each edge `h[i]h[i+1]` the farthest vertex `j` is the one that maximizes the area of the parallelogram spanned by the edge and the vector to `j`.  
The while‑loop moves `j` forward exactly until this area stops increasing, which is precisely the definition of an antipodal pair.  
Because `j` never moves backward, every antipodal pair is considered once. ∎



#### Lemma 4  
The maximum squared distance found by the rotating calipers loop equals the diameter of the convex hull.

*Proof.*  
By Lemma&nbsp;3 every antipodal pair is examined.  
For a convex polygon the farthest pair of vertices is always an antipodal pair.  
Thus the maximum distance over all examined pairs is the diameter. ∎



#### Theorem  
The algorithm outputs the maximum possible distance between two sparkling points.

*Proof.*  

1. By Lemma&nbsp;1 sparkling points are exactly the boundary points of the convex hull.  
2. By Lemma&nbsp;2 the hull computed by the algorithm contains all sparkling points.  
3. By Lemma&nbsp;4 the rotating calipers part returns the diameter of this hull, i.e. the largest distance between any two of its vertices.  
4. Therefore the algorithm returns the largest distance between any two sparkling points. ∎



--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 5.  Complexity Analysis

*Sorting points:* `O(n log n)`  
*Building hull:* `O(n)`  
*Rotating calipers:* `O(m)` where `m ≤ n`  
Overall time: `O(n log n)`  
Memory usage: `O(n)` for storing the points and the hull.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

### 6.  Reference Implementation  (C++17)

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Point {
    long long x, y;
    bool operator<(const Point& other) const {
        return x < other.x || (x == other.x && y < other.y);
    }
};

Point operator-(const Point& a, const Point& b) {
    return {a.x - b.x, a.y - b.y};
}

long long cross(const Point& a, const Point& b) {
    return a.x * b.y - a.y * b.x;
}

long long dist2(const Point& a, const Point& b) {
    long long dx = a.x - b.x;
    long long dy = a.y - b.y;
    return dx * dx + dy * dy;
}

// Convex hull – monotone chain, keeps collinear boundary points
vector<Point> convexHull(vector<Point> pts) {
    sort(pts.begin(), pts.end());
    int n = pts.size();
    vector<Point> lower, upper;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        while (lower.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(lower[lower.size()-1] - lower[lower.size()-2],
                     pts[i] - lower[lower.size()-1]) < 0)
            lower.pop_back();
        lower.push_back(pts[i]);
    }
    for (int i = n-1; i >= 0; --i) {
        while (upper.size() >= 2 &&
               cross(upper[upper.size()-1] - upper[upper.size()-2],
                     pts[i] - upper[upper.size()-1]) < 0)
            upper.pop_back();
        upper.push_back(pts[i]);
    }
    // Concatenate, removing duplicate endpoints
    lower.pop_back();
    upper.pop_back();
    lower.insert(lower.end(), upper.begin(), upper.end());
    return lower;
}

// Rotating calipers – diameter of convex polygon
long long diameter(const vector<Point>& hull) {
    int m = hull.size();
    if (m == 1) return 0;
    if (m == 2) return dist2(hull[0], hull[1]);

    long long best = 0;
    int j = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        int ni = (i + 1) % m;
        // Move j while area increases
        while (cross(hull[ni] - hull[i], hull[(j + 1) % m] - hull[i]) >
               cross(hull[ni] - hull[i], hull[j] - hull[i]))
            j = (j + 1) % m;
        best = max(best, dist2(hull[i], hull[j]));
        best = max(best, dist2(hull[ni], hull[j]));
    }
    return best;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    int n;
    if (!(cin >> n)) return 0;
    vector<Point> pts(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) cin >> pts[i].x >> pts[i].y;
    vector<Point> hull = convexHull(pts);
    cout << diameter(hull) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

The program follows exactly the algorithm proven correct above and conforms to the GNU++17 compiler.

